    <h2 id="tart-cherry-science">The Science Behind Tart Cherry Gummies: Anthocyanins, Inflammation, and Sleep</h2>

    <p>Tart cherry (<em>Prunus cerasus</em>) is not a trendy superfood — it is one of the most rigorously studied natural anti-inflammatory compounds in nutritional science. The Montmorency cultivar, which dominates both clinical research and commercial supplements, contains over 300 bioactive compounds including anthocyanins (cyanidin-3-glucosylrutinoside and cyanidin-3-rutinoside), flavonoids, phenolic acids, and one of the only food-based sources of exogenous melatonin. These compounds work through multiple pharmacological mechanisms that have been validated in over 30 peer-reviewed clinical trials since 2006.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">20x</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">more vitamin A than sweet cherries — tart Montmorency cherries deliver <strong>1,283 IU of vitamin A per 100g</strong> compared to just 64 IU in sweet Bing cherries. They also contain 12,800 ORAC units per 100g (a measure of antioxidant capacity), exceeding blueberries, pomegranates, and most commonly consumed fruits.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The primary therapeutic mechanism of tart cherry is COX-1 and COX-2 enzyme inhibition — the exact same pathway targeted by ibuprofen and aspirin. A landmark 2012 study at Oregon Health & Science University found that tart cherry juice reduced inflammatory biomarkers (CRP, IL-6, TNF-alpha) by 25-40% in osteoarthritis patients after 21 days of supplementation. Unlike pharmaceutical NSAIDs, tart cherry delivers this anti-inflammatory effect without the gastrointestinal, renal, and cardiovascular risks associated with long-term NSAID use.</p>

