    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Tart Cherry Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the proven benefits of tart cherry gummies?</summary>
      <p>Tart cherry gummies deliver concentrated Montmorency cherry extract rich in anthocyanins with five clinically validated benefits: reduced joint inflammation via COX enzyme inhibition, improved sleep quality and duration through natural melatonin, accelerated exercise recovery with 13-23% less muscle soreness, lowered serum uric acid for gout management, and potent antioxidant protection with an ORAC value of 12,800 per 100g.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much tart cherry should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>Clinical studies demonstrating benefits used 480-960mg of tart cherry extract daily. Most gummies provide 500-1000mg per serving. For sleep, take 30-60 minutes before bed. For joint health and recovery, consistent daily supplementation over 4-8 weeks produces the strongest results. Doses up to 1500mg have been used safely in clinical settings.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do tart cherry gummies actually help with sleep?</summary>
      <p>Yes. Tart cherry contains natural melatonin (13.5ng/g) and inhibits tryptophan degradation, increasing serotonin and melatonin synthesis. A 2018 study found tart cherry juice increased sleep time by 84 minutes in adults with insomnia. A 2012 European Journal of Nutrition study found significantly improved sleep duration and quality compared to placebo.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are tart cherry gummies good for gout?</summary>
      <p>A 2012 study of 633 gout patients found cherry intake reduced gout flare risk by 35%, increasing to 75% when combined with allopurinol. Anthocyanins inhibit xanthine oxidase, the same enzyme targeted by prescription gout medications. Tart cherry gummies provide standardized dosing with lower sugar than cherry juice. They should complement, not replace, prescribed gout medications.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Tart cherry gummies vs. tart cherry juice — which is better?</summary>
      <p>Both deliver the same anthocyanins, but gummies offer advantages: 2-4g sugar per serving versus 20-25g for juice, standardized extract doses for reliable dosing, longer shelf stability, and higher daily compliance. Juice provides more hydration. For sustained supplementation, gummies are more practical — most users abandon tart cherry juice within 2-3 weeks due to the intense sour taste.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take tart cherry gummies with other supplements?</summary>
      <p>Tart cherry pairs well with turmeric/curcumin (enhanced anti-inflammatory), omega-3 fish oil (joint health), and magnesium (sleep). Use caution with blood thinners (anthocyanins have mild antiplatelet effects) and avoid stacking with melatonin supplements. Consult your physician if taking NSAIDs, as tart cherry inhibits the same COX enzymes.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for tart cherry gummies to work?</summary>
      <p>Sleep benefits appear within 1-3 days (natural melatonin effect). Exercise recovery benefits appear within 24-48 hours. Joint health improvements require 4-8 weeks of consistent daily supplementation. Uric acid reduction is measurable within 2-4 weeks. Benefits are cumulative and diminish within days of discontinuation.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the difference between Montmorency and Balaton tart cherries?</summary>
      <p>Montmorency (bright red skin, yellow flesh) has the highest anthocyanin concentration and over 95% of clinical research support. Balaton (darker flesh, slightly sweeter) has lower anthocyanin content. Michigan produces 75% of US tart cherries, primarily Montmorency. When choosing tart cherry gummies, look for "Montmorency" on the label — products listing generic "tart cherry" may use lower-potency varieties.</p>
    </details>

